'''Project Canterbury''' (sometimes abbreviated as PC) is an online archive of material related to the history of [[Anglicanism]]. It was founded by Richard Mammana, Jr. in 1999,<ref>{{cite web |title=About Project Canterbury |website=Project Canterbury |url=http://anglicanhistory.org/about.html |access-date=15 October 2017 }}</ref> and is hosted by the non-profit [[Society of Archbishop Justus]].<ref name=Brown2013>{{cite journal |last=Brown |first=Terry M. |author-link=Terry Brown (bishop) |date=2013 |title=Pacific Anglicanism: Online Bibliographical Resources |journal=[[The Contemporary Pacific]] |volume=25 |issue=2 |pages=341-348 |url=http://scholarspace.manoa.hawaii.edu/bitstream/10125/33582/1/v25n2-341-348.pdf |format=pdf |hdl=10125/33582 }}</ref> The episcopal patrons of the site are [[Geoffrey Rowell]] [[Bishop of Gibraltar in Europe]] and [[Terry Brown (bishop)|Terry Brown]], retired bishop of [[Diocese of Malaita|Malaita]] in the [[Church of the Province of Melanesia]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Advisory Board |website=Project Canterbury |url=http://anglicanhistory.org/board.html |access-date=15 October 2017 }}</ref> Volunteer transcribers prepare material for the site, which incorporates modern scholarly material, primary source texts, photographic images and engravings.<ref name=Brown2013/>

